# tvOS — TV Platform Rules

Apple TV (tvOS) uses Swift and optionally TVML. Not HTML5; separate codebase. **Cold launch** must stay lean — async all I/O, sequence heavy init so the UI never freezes. **Simulator ≠ device** — always profile on real Apple TV hardware.

## Human Interface Guidelines (10-foot UX)

- **Distance:** ~10 feet; large legible type, high contrast, clear hierarchy.
- **Focus engine:** One focused element at a time. Parallax on focused icons. Siri Remote D-pad/touch moves focus predictably. No tiny targets.
- **Motion:** Short, purposeful animations. No gratuitous motion that delays key feedback.
- **Official:** Apple tvOS HIG and App Programming Guide for tvOS.

## Top Shelf and discovery

- Wide banner above app row: static and dynamic content for hero art and deep links (continue watching).
- Requires associated domains / valid JSON payloads per Apple's format. Plan assets and CDN early.
- Store-facing: refresh when catalog updates.

## Storage and on-demand resources

- Apple TV has **limited persistent storage**. Large caches may be purged. Use **On-Demand Resources (ODR)** or streaming. Don't assume local caches survive.

---

## Performance

- **Reduce launch time.** Distinguish cold vs warm launch. Defer non-essential init.
- **Instruments + Organizer** for launch metrics.
- **ODR** shrinks initial install / first launch payload.
- **Simulator ≠ device** for GPU and thermal behavior. Profile on device.
- **Main thread** must stay responsive. Async all I/O and heavy decode.
- **Sequencing:** Decode/parse large JSON on background queue or `Task.detached`, not main actor. Streaming or incremental decode for very large payloads.
- **Component pooling:** Reuse UIKit/SwiftUI views. Instantiation is expensive on TV hardware.

---

## OEM architecture

**Sources:** Apple — App Programming Guide for tvOS, HIG "Designing for tvOS", launch-time docs.

- **UIKit / SwiftUI / TVUIKit.** Top Shelf for featured content. Client-server patterns for catalog apps.
- **HIG:** 10-foot, obvious focus (parallax, elevation), horizontal grids, Siri Remote (Menu, Play/Pause). No non-standard gestures except games.
- **Lifecycle:** Scenes; limited local storage — prefer network + cache discipline. Cold launch optimization, ODR for large assets.
- **Dark mode** and system appearance — harmonize chrome with tvOS.

---

## First paint

**(1)** Show UI immediately, **(2)** first interactive screen ASAP.

### Swift / UIKit
- **Launch Screen** (storyboard or asset) for instant branding. Root VC with lightweight loading state (splash + `UIActivityIndicatorView` or SwiftUI `ProgressView`).
- **Do not block** `application(_:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:)` with sync network, large disk reads, or heavy parsing. Use `Task {}` / `DispatchQueue.global()` / async-await. Sequence or chunk very large JSON.
- **Dismiss splash only** when first real screen is laid out and visible.

### SwiftUI
- Root view: splash or progress first. `.task` / `.onAppear` for async data. Swap to content when ready. Small initial view tree.

### TVML (if used)
- Loading template immediately. Fetch/parse in background. Push/replace when ready.

### Startup efficiency
- Prefetch images and config **after** loading UI is on screen. Prioritize time-to-interactive.

---

## Layout

- tvOS runs at fixed point scales (@1x / @2x for 1080p / 4K). Use **integral points** for frames, spacing, grid cells.
- Define layout constants as **whole numbers**. Round once at layout time, not per frame.
- Auto Layout / SwiftUI with integer spacing. Fractional values during animation OK; snap to int at rest.

---

## Lifecycle

- App launch, foreground/background, termination. **Restore focus** after returning from background (HIG: user should not lose context).
- **Scene lifecycle:** `sceneWillEnterForeground` / `sceneDidEnterBackground` — pause playback, save state, refresh stale data.
- **Agent guidance:** Align focus and layout with HIG. Optimize cold launch. Use ODR for large assets.

## Tooling

- Xcode; Apple TV simulator and device debugging.
- Signing and provisioning for App Store and TestFlight.
